<font color="#FF0000">COWARDICE AND BRAVERY</font><br>
<tt>Sat Feb  7 22:29:34 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Josh P.<br><br>
Thank you for your history. I better understand who you are and appreciate knowing something of who I am talking to. I know it is hard to post a biography like yours in a group like this. I too was a protester, though I did not leave the U.S. <br><br>
Edward.<br>
While I understand the intensity of your beliefs, I encourage you to remember &quot;Judge No One&quot; applies to all who were caught up in the war. People made decisions that were life changing in the most difficult of times. Some of the decisions made I will never understand, some of those decisions you will never understand. Some of them we all, with hind sight do not now agree with. <br><br>
I think that the decision to leave the country, maybe forever was a very difficult decision for people to make. It took courage to stand up in the face of a pro-war mentality, and act on your convictions. It is courageous to take a step that says I don't support a war and will not participate in it. We could not stop the war, but we did have the power to make sure we did not participate in it. Edward, I appreciate your view on these actions being wrong, but don't confuse this with being a coward. Very few people who left the country did so because they were cowards. Almost all of those who did, did it because of political or moral beliefs.<br><br>
I think Ed is right (if it was you who said it), that we cannot control our children, only influence them by our actions throughout the course of their upbringing. I also have a teen age son, and I do not want him fighting in any war. I love him too much, and am afraid that he might die. I also realize that it is not my decision. He will make his own choice if asked, as we made ours. I will support him no matter what he chooses, and hopefully he will seek my council and I will be able to help him make the right choice. That being what is right for him, not right for me.<br><br>
As for the war against Saadam/Iraq, it smells like the Vietnam war, in that it doesn't have a clear objective, is without clear support internationally or at home and could be a quagmire that has no forseeable end. I can't figure out what is right to do, but my gut tells me if we do it Clinton's way we will be very sorry.<br><br>
Help me with these questions?<br>
1. Who will benefit from our engaging Iraq?<br>
2. What is in it for the US (people not corporations)?<br>
3. What is our objective and is it obtainable?<br>
4. Are their other alternatives that we have not yet    considered?<br>
5. When we shut down the flow of oil from Iraq, our oil    and gas prices went up as did the profits of US oil    companies. How was this in the interest of the US people?<br>
6. What about a policy of deterence? (If you use chemical or    biological weapons, we'll bomb x,y, or z). Is this a    viable alternative?<br>
7. If we go to war, what is the objective and how will we be    able to exit? <br>
8. Is this a US or a UN decision, and under who's egis do we    fight under? If it is the UN, and they say stop, will we    stop?<br><br>
I don't trust that our government has answers to these questions that will satisfy me. Lots of jingoistic statements, lots of platitudes and slogans. But mostly I think it is for the benefit of the corporations not the people. <br><br>
Josh, If the war happens so will protests. I am sure many of us will be joining you, Vets and non-Vets alike. On the other side, we will see Vets and Draft Dodgers and anti-war protesters as well. We have all changed since the 60's. What was is no longer.
